rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: This pitfall consists in creating an ontology element and failing to provide human readable annotations attached to it. Consequently, ontology elements lack annotation properties that label them (e.g. rdfs:label, lemon:LexicalEntry, skos:prefLabel or skos:altLabel) or that define them (e.g. rdfs:comment or dc:description). This pitfall is related to the guidelines provided in [5].

rdf:Description.oops:hasName: Missing domain or range in properties
rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: Object and/or datatype properties without domain or range (or none of them) are included in the ontology.

The domain or range (or both) of a property (relationships and attributes) is defined by stating more than one rdfs:domain or rdfs:range statements. In OWL multiple rdfs:domain or rdfs:range axioms are allowed, but they are interpreted as conjunction, being, therefore, equivalent to the construct owl:intersectionOf. This pitfall is related to the common error that appears when defining domains and ranges described in [7].
rdf:Description.oops:hasName: Defining multiple domains or ranges in properties

rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: A class whose name refers to two or more different concepts is created.
rdf:Description.oops:hasName: Merging different concepts in the same class

rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: The ontology lacks disjoint axioms between classes or between properties that should be defined as disjoint. This pitfall is related with the guidelines provided in [6], [2] and [7].

This pitfall refers to the creation of a class with the only goal of classifying the instances that do not belong to any of its sibling classes (classes with which the miscellaneous problematic class shares a common direct ancestor).

rdf:Description.oops:hasAffectedElement: There are elements following different naming conventions as for example: https://sakuna.ph/Extra-tropicalStorm https://sakuna.ph/GroundMovement
rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: The ontology elements are not named following the same convention (for example CamelCase or use of delimiters as "-" or "_") . Some notions about naming conventions are provided in [2].
rdf:Description.oops:hasName: Using different naming conventions in the ontology

rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: This pitfall appears when any relationship (except for those that are defined as symmetric properties using owl:SymmetricProperty) does not have an inverse relationship (owl:inverseOf) defined within the ontology.
